[The report on the 2 cases of WPV1-associated disease in Pakistan is confirmation of the earlier media report posted on ProMED-mail (see Poliomyelitis update (21): global (Nigeria), Pakistan 20190321.6379811). A disturbing addition is the 15 positive environmental samples reported from Pakistan with dates of collection 27 Feb 2019 to 12 Mar 2019 from sites located in all 4 provinces of the country, signaling continued widespread circulation of the WPV in Pakistan. Further discomforting information is that since the beginning of this year (1 Jan 2019) there have been a total of 65 environmental-positive samples in Pakistan, whereas in the entire year last year (2018), there were a total of 140 positive environmental samples. It is possible that this is good news and represents enhanced environmental sampling (remembering the 2 adages: "Seek and ye shall find," or its corollary, "Don't look, and it ain't there." Or perhaps this is not-so-good news that this year (2019) has more circulation of the WPV1 in the country. Time will tell. Do read the media report below to get a feel for the huge effort ongoing in Pakistan to interrupt transmission, as well as some of the obstacles faced in the country.

Further disconcerting information in the above report is the continued identification of cVDPV2 in Nigeria, with 2 newly confirmed cases: 1 in Kwara (a relatively new state reporting transmission) and 1 in Borno state, where there had been WPV1 circulating in 2016. The key concern here is the persistent presence of a susceptible population that facilitates the circulation of the cVDPV2.

Hopefully the absence of reports of additional cases of cVDPVs in other countries where cases have been identified in the past year is a reflection of good control measures implemented, leading to interruption of transmission of the cVDPVs.

For a map showing the locations of cases of WPV and cVDPV, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

